  mermaid diagrams in
  `frontend/src/components/chat-detail/ChatDetail.js`'s
  `useLayoutEffect` save/restore (a user refreshing a chat such
  as `/chat/ec60d4dd-9bac-45af-84e7-bc7e35022378` from a non-zero
  scroll position landed slightly above or below the saved
  position; chats without diagrams restored precisely). Two
  layout-mismatch invariants were violated together. SAVE side:
  the legacy `String(window.scrollY)` save was layout-dependent,
  so any height delta in mermaid blocks above the viewport
  between save and restore drifted the user; closed by recording
  an anchor-based `{ msgIdx, offset }` JSON keyed off the
  topmost in-viewport `MessageBubble`'s `data-msg-idx` attribute
  (added in
  [`MessageBubble.js`](frontend/src/components/chat-detail/MessageBubble.js)'s
  outer `<Box>` and threaded through
  [`MessageList.js`](frontend/src/components/chat-detail/MessageList.js)),
  with a `Number(raw)` fallback path on `JSON.parse` failure for
  the legacy `sessionStorage` format. RESTORE side: the
  `contentVisibility: 'auto'` hint on `MermaidBlock`'s outer
  `<Box>` skips layout/paint of off-screen mermaid blocks at the
  static `containIntrinsicSize: '0 400px'` placeholder height,
  so when `useLayoutEffect` measured `anchor.offsetTop` at
  `scrollY = 0` every block above the saved scroll position was
  at the 400px placeholder; the post-`scrollTo`
  `content-visibility: auto` re-evaluation materialized blocks
  now in or near the new viewport, replacing 400px with their
  actual 600-1000px SVG heights, shifting `anchor.offsetTop` by
  the cumulative delta while `scrollY` stayed put -- landing the
  user exactly that delta off the saved anchor. Closed by
  chasing that shift after the initial `scrollTo` with a
  `requestAnimationFrame`-driven re-scroll loop (capped at 5
  frames as a safety net, 2-3 typical in practice) inside the
  same `useLayoutEffect`: each iteration re-reads
  `document.querySelector('[data-msg-idx="${msgIdx}"]').offsetTop`,
  computes `newTargetY = offsetTop + offset`, and re-scrolls when
  `Math.abs(newTargetY - window.scrollY) > 1`; the 1-px tolerance
  prevents a no-op `scrollTo` from re-triggering layout work, and
  the loop is skipped entirely on the legacy plain-number fallback
  / no-saved-entry / anchor-missing paths. Cleanup
  `cancelAnimationFrame`s the in-flight rAF. An earlier attempt
  threaded a `disableContentVisibility` boolean through
  `MessageList` → `MessageBubble` → `MessageMarkdown` →
  `MermaidBlock` to disable the `'auto'` hint for the first
  paint; that approach was reverted because flipping the gate
  back to `'auto'` one frame after the restore shrinks every
  off-screen mermaid block from its rendered height back to the
  400px placeholder, shifting the anchor while `scrollY` stays
  put, and browser scroll-anchoring does not catch a
  `content-visibility`-driven layout shift -- so the drift
  symptom returned. Pinned in
  [`theme-transitions.mdc`](theme-transitions.mdc) under "Two
  CSS containment hints" (the `data-msg-idx` SAVE bullet plus
  the rAF re-scroll RESTORE paragraph). Not regression-pinned
  because the frontend has no JS test harness, so the invariant
  is enforced by the cross-referenced rule and by manual
  verification only -- refresh
  `/chat/ec60d4dd-9bac-45af-84e7-bc7e35022378` and
  `/chat/7be71d40-07cb-46de-8203-266e17c97ae7` from a non-zero
  scroll position and confirm the user lands precisely where
  they were after a one-frame rAF settle, then refresh a
  diagram-free chat to confirm the legacy-format
  `sessionStorage` fallback path still restores precisely.
  **Continued fix.** The 5-frame rAF chase loop above proved
  insufficient on long diagram-heavy chats: rAF callbacks run
  *between* paints and read `anchor.offsetTop` against the
  layout as of the previous paint, while
  `content-visibility: auto` re-evaluation runs as part of the
  rendering update step *between* rAFs -- so each `scrollTo`
  triggered another wave of materialization that the next rAF
  saw, and each new wave pulled MORE blocks into the viewport
  buffer in a cascade that frequently exceeded the 5-frame cap.
  When the cascade fit in 5 frames the user landed exact; when
  it did not, the residual was visible drift, producing a
  timing-dependent "sometimes lands exact, sometimes off"
  symptom on the same two URLs. Closed by adding a layout-axis
  sibling to `mermaidRenderCache`:
  [`mermaidHeightCache`](frontend/src/utils/mermaidHeightCache.js)
  (a session-scoped `sessionStorage`-backed source-keyed
  height map) plus
  [`useMermaidBlockHeight`](frontend/src/hooks/useMermaidBlockHeight.js)
  (a `ResizeObserver` hook attached to each `MermaidBlock`'s
  outer `<Box>` that records the rendered height back to the
  cache as the block materializes). `MermaidBlock` reads the
  recorded height via the hook's lazy `useState` initializer
  and uses it as
  `containIntrinsicSize: \`0 ${persistedHeight ?? 400}px\``
  -- so on every refresh after the first the placeholder
  matches the actual rendered height, the layout above the
  scroll anchor is deterministic before the first `scrollTo`
  runs, and the rAF chase loop becomes the safety net for the
  residual unmeasured-block case (first-ever load of a chat,
  `sessionStorage` unavailable, or a source the user scrolled
  past too fast for the observer to fire) rather than the
  primary mechanism. The 5-frame cap was also replaced with
  stable-frames-based convergence (exit after the position is
  stable for 2 consecutive frames, with a 30-frame safety
  ceiling) so the loop both exits early on the typical fast-
  converge case and tolerates the rare slow-converge case it
  could not handle before. Pinned in
  [`theme-transitions.mdc`](theme-transitions.mdc) under "Two
  CSS containment hints" (the persisted-`containIntrinsicSize`
  bullet and the stable-frames RESTORE paragraph),
  [`frontend-hooks.mdc`](frontend-hooks.mdc) under the new
  `useMermaidBlockHeight` entry, and
  [`mermaid-rendering.mdc`](mermaid-rendering.mdc) under
  "Render cache and queue" → "`mermaidHeightCache`" (the
  layout-axis sibling subsection). Not regression-pinned
  because the frontend has no JS test harness, so the invariant
  is enforced by the cross-referenced rules and by manual
  verification only -- open
  `/chat/ec60d4dd-9bac-45af-84e7-bc7e35022378` cold (no
  `mermaid-block-heights` entry in `sessionStorage` yet), scroll
  mid-page, refresh, confirm precise landing; refresh again
  from a fresh non-zero scroll position to confirm the warm-
  cache case; then refresh a diagram-free chat to confirm the
  legacy-plain-number `sessionStorage` fallback path is
  unaffected.
- the mermaid SVG cross-fade outgoing-layer cancellation gap in
  `frontend/src/hooks/useSvgCrossFade.js` (consumed by
  `MermaidDiagramSurface`'s outgoing-layer JSX). A user who
  flipped OS-level reduced-motion during the ~200ms cross-fade
  window saw the outgoing SVG stick on top of the incoming SVG
  until the next svg change for that block (typically the next
  theme toggle), because the global
  `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` rule in
  `frontend/src/index.css` overrides the keyframe to
  `animation: none !important` mid-fade, which fires
  `animationcancel` (not `animationend`) on the outgoing layer;
  React's `onAnimationEnd` JSX prop is `onanimationend` only and
  there is no `onAnimationCancel` shorthand, so
  `setOutgoingSvg(null)` was never called for the cancelled fade.
  Closed by exposing a new `outgoingRef` from the hook (the
  consumer attaches it to the outgoing `<Box>`) and adding a
  `useEffect([outgoingSvg])` in the hook that calls
  `outgoingRef.current.addEventListener('animationcancel', () =>
  setOutgoingSvg(null))` whenever an outgoing layer is mounted,
  with cleanup that removes the listener before the next
  remount-on-rapid-toggle swaps the DOM node out from under it.
  Pinned in [`theme-transitions.mdc`](theme-transitions.mdc) under
  "SVG content cross-fade (mermaid diagrams)" (the
  `animationcancel` listener is the fifth load-bearing piece,
  flagged as a correctness invariant rather than a perf
  optimization) and in [`frontend-hooks.mdc`](frontend-hooks.mdc)
  under the `useSvgCrossFade` entry (return shape now includes
  `outgoingRef`). Not regression-pinned because the frontend has
  no JS test harness, so the invariant is enforced by the
  cross-referenced rules and by manual verification only --
  toggle dark/light on a chat with at least one mermaid diagram,
  flip the OS-level reduced-motion preference while the ~200ms
  cross-fade is in flight, and confirm the outgoing layer
  unmounts within the same frame the keyframe is cancelled
  instead of sticking until the next theme toggle.
- the cross-message mermaid singleton race during dual-theme
  prerender in
  `frontend/src/components/chat-detail/ChatDetail.js`'s fetch
  effect. On a diagram-heavy multi-message chat (e.g.
  `/chat/ec60d4dd-9bac-45af-84e7-bc7e35022378`), some diagrams
  rendered with the wrong theme on first paint or after the
  first dark/light toggle from the cache, because the legacy
  fused per-message closure ran the outer
  `Promise.all(rawMessages.map(...))` over an inner
  `prerenderMermaidDiagrams(content, darkMode)` /
  `prerenderMermaidDiagrams(content, !darkMode)` pair. Each
  `prerenderMermaidDiagrams` call flips
  `mermaid.initialize({ theme: ... })` on the global mermaid
  singleton and then runs its own internal `Promise.all` over
  the diagrams in one message; the in-message sequential `await`
  serialized only the two calls for ONE message, but across
  messages the dual-theme pairs interleaved freely. Once any
  message's B-pass call wrote `theme: !darkMode` to the
  singleton, mermaid's `processAndSetConfigs` `reset()`-to-
  baseline at the start of every `mermaid.render` propagated the
  flipped theme to any other message's A-pass render that had
  not yet captured its config -- producing a wrong-themed SVG
  cached under `(source, darkMode)`. Closed by restructuring
  the fetch effect into three sequential outer phases: Phase A
  is `Promise.all` over messages calling `prepareMarkdownHtml`
  only (no mermaid state at all); Phase B is `Promise.all` over
  messages calling `prerenderMermaidDiagrams(content, darkMode)`
  for the user's active theme; Phase C is `Promise.all` over
  messages calling `prerenderMermaidDiagrams(content,
  !darkMode)` for the cache-warm pass. The sequential `await`
  between Phase B and Phase C gives each
  `prerenderMermaidDiagrams` call uncontested ownership of the
  singleton for its full lifetime, since every concurrent
  render within a phase shares the same theme. Pinned in
  [`mermaid-rendering.mdc`](mermaid-rendering.mdc) under "Render
  cache and queue" → `prerenderMermaidDiagrams` writer (the
  three-phase shape and the "do not nest the dual-theme pair
  inside a `Promise.all` over messages" invariant). Not
  regression-pinned because the frontend has no JS test harness,
  so the invariant is enforced by the cross-referenced rule and
  by manual verification only -- open a diagram-heavy multi-
  message chat such as
  `/chat/ec60d4dd-9bac-45af-84e7-bc7e35022378`, inspect each
  diagram's `stroke` / `fill` colors against the active theme
  on first paint, then toggle dark/light from cache and
  re-inspect; every diagram should match the active theme on
  first paint and after every toggle.
- the AppBar (title bar) painting near-black in dark mode after
  the CSS-variables migration in
  `frontend/src/theme/buildTheme.js`'s `MuiAppBar` config. After
  migrating from `createTheme(c, mode)` (one theme per scheme,
  rebuilt on every toggle) to a single
  `createTheme({ cssVariables, colorSchemes: { light, dark } })`,
  the AppBar paints `#121212` in dark mode -- the
  `darkColors.background.default` value -- instead of the
  `#005e80` blue from `sharedColors.primary.dark` that `main`
  used in both schemes. Root cause: MUI 7's default `MuiAppBar`
  ships a scheme-conditional override that, when
  `ownerState.enableColorOnDark` is `false` (the default),
  applies `theme.applyStyles('dark', { backgroundColor:
  theme.vars?.palette.AppBar?.darkBg })` -- which falls back to
  `palette.background.default`. That conditional is generated at
  higher specificity than the static `styleOverrides.root.background:
  var(--mui-palette-primary-dark)` rule below, so the static
  override loses the cascade in the dark scheme. (The bug did
  not surface on `main` because the pre-migration per-mode theme
  rebuild had no scheme-conditional default to compete against
  for any single emitted theme.) Closed by adding
  `defaultProps: { enableColorOnDark: true }` to the
  `MuiAppBar` config alongside the existing `styleOverrides`,
  which gates the dark-only override out and lets the static
  `--mui-palette-primary-dark` rule apply in both schemes.
  Pinned in [`theme-transitions.mdc`](theme-transitions.mdc)
  under "Centralize via MUI theme `styleOverrides`" (the
  `MuiAppBar.defaultProps.enableColorOnDark: true` invariant,
  flagged as a load-bearing wire-up similar to the
  `colorSchemeSelector: 'data-mui-color-scheme'` invariant in
  the "CSS variables palette" section). Not regression-pinned
  because the frontend has no JS test harness, so the invariant
  is enforced by the cross-referenced rule and by manual
  verification only -- open any chat in dark mode and confirm
  the title bar is `#005e80` blue (the shared `primary.dark`
  palette token), not `#121212` near-black; toggle to light
  mode and confirm the AppBar stays the same blue.

When the next deferred bug surfaces, add the marker rather than
silently rewriting the code path, then cite that file from this
section.

# Hardcoded user-specific values

User-specific hardcoded paths, usernames, or project lists are
**always** a bug. If you must add one temporarily, flag it with
`# TODO(bug):` and include the reasoning.

# `TODO(bug):` vs plain `TODO:`

- `TODO(bug):` is reserved for **known-broken behavior** we have
  chosen not to fix yet. It says "this is wrong, don't rely on it".
- Plain `TODO:` is for cleanups, future enhancements, and generic
  "revisit later" notes. It says "this works, but could be nicer".

Do not use `TODO(bug):` for generic cleanups; the distinction is what
lets a future contributor grep for real defects.
